East 23rd Street, st, adjoining and east of the S. E. corner of Lexington Avenue (right), showing prominently the College of the City of New York, established in 1848 as the Free Academy. It acquired its present title in 1866. This structure was replaced with a modern building about 1926

About 1912

H.N. Tiemann, photo
Gift of the Urbrook Collection

Neg. #3995

E. 23rd Street, west from Lexington Ave., showing mainly the north side extending to 4th Ave. At that point appears the old building housing Packard Business School and the towering Metropolitan building and its tower. The utilitarian 12-story loft building nearing completion is No. 115-9.
The photographer is standing outside of the old City College and shows at the left a portion of the 5-story building at the S.W. corner of Lexington Ave. and 23rd St.
1914–5
Gift of George H. Hahn
(71 West 35th Street)

text:
East 23rd Street, at, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Lexington Ave. The Lexington Ave., side of this view will form the site of the Hotel George Washington. Note on the right the Kenmore Hall under construction.
February 4, 1928
P.L. Sperr.

East 23rd Street, north side, at Lexington Avenue, showing two individual views of each corner. The photographer's vantage point is the Children's Court building on East 22nd Street. The direction is northward across the clearance where the old City College stood. The 13 story office building shown at the N.W. corner is the Fifth National Bank Bldg. The low structures at the N.E. corner will be razed for the future Hotel George Washington. In the background appears the American Book Co. building on Lexington Avenue, at 26th Street.

March 12, 1928

P.L. Sperr

Lexington Ave. (foreground) at the S.E. corner of East 23rd Street (left) showing the old College of the City of New York under demolition. A modern school building was erected here later to replace same. On the left appears several structures on the north side of East 23rd Street, between Lexington and Third Aves. The spire appearing on the right is of the Swedish Lutheran Church on East 22nd Street. This set consists of a negative and a positive.
February 7, 1928.
Robert A. Knudsten.

Lexington Ave., north from East 23rd Street.
October 2, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.

129 to 115 East 23rd Street, adjoining and west of the N.W. corner of Lexington Avenue, showing the newly constructed Gramercy Theatre (movie) at No. 129-27. Note the new location of the O'Brien Stationary Company which was formerly at No. 150. An explosion of great force occurred in the month of October, 1938, caused by the ignition of vapors in the cleaning establishment adjoining the theatre. Three died and several were seriously injured.
June 1938
George D. Chinn
